Applying different variable embedding sequences in graphs is useful to maximize relevant variation like applying 'maximally different start/end points of each workflow (problem/solution type/metric)' as well as 'maximally different connection types' and 'maximally different connections between workflows' which can make this graph 'usefully specific', which is a way to 'apply maximal differences in graphs in a structure that identifies useful connections'.
Another way to apply 'maximal differences in graphs' is 'embedding interface variable connections randomly, like by applying maximally irrelevant interface variables as spectrums that are also connected by each workflow (as well as connecting the problem/solution)' or 'embedding interface spectrum intersection graphs' as 'graphs to connect each workflow to or graphs to differentiate each workflow'.
